<Learn
  title="Glossary"
  description="Deliverability and cold-email vocabulary, defined plainly."
  reading="5 min read"
  updated="2026-04-12"
>
  <h2>A</h2>
  <h3>ARF (Abuse Reporting Format)</h3>
  <p>The standardised format mailbox providers use to report spam complaints back to senders. Warmbly ingests ARF reports where available.</p>

  <h3>Alignment</h3>
  <p>The DMARC requirement that the authenticated domain (from SPF or DKIM) match the visible "From:" domain. Relaxed alignment matches at the organisational level; strict requires exact equality.</p>

  <h2>B</h2>
  <h3>Bounce</h3>
  <p>A failed delivery. Hard bounces (invalid mailbox, blocked domain) suppress immediately. Soft bounces (mailbox full, temporary outage) are retried with backoff and suppressed if persistent.</p>

  <h3>BIMI</h3>
  <p>Brand Indicators for Message Identification. Lets you publish a verified logo that some clients display next to your messages. Requires DMARC <code>p=quarantine</code> or stricter, plus a VMC certificate for full display.</p>

  <h2>C</h2>
  <h3>Cold email</h3>
  <p>Unsolicited mail to a recipient with whom you have no prior relationship. Distinct from spam by intent: cold mail is targeted, relevant, and gives the recipient a real way to say no.</p>

  <h3>Complaint rate</h3>
  <p>Percentage of delivered messages marked as spam by recipients. Google's bulk-sender threshold is 0.10%. Above 0.30% is in the danger zone.</p>

  <h2>D</h2>
  <h3>DEK (Data Encryption Key)</h3>
  <p>A symmetric key used to encrypt application-level data. Generated by KMS and stored encrypted; the plaintext form is briefly cached for hot paths.</p>

  <h3>DKIM</h3>
  <p>Cryptographic signature that proves a message was authorised by the domain's key holder and not modified in transit.</p>

  <h3>DMARC</h3>
  <p>The policy that ties SPF and DKIM to the visible From: domain and tells receivers what to do on failure.</p>

  <h2>F</h2>
  <h3>FBL (Feedback Loop)</h3>
  <p>A direct channel from a mailbox provider that forwards spam-complaint events to the sender so they can suppress the recipient.</p>

  <h2>H</h2>
  <h3>HMAC signature</h3>
  <p>The cryptographic signature on a webhook delivery that lets you verify the call really came from Warmbly and wasn't tampered with.</p>

  <h2>I</h2>
  <h3>Inbox placement</h3>
  <p>Share of accepted messages that land in the recipient's primary inbox (not spam, not promotions). The metric that actually matters.</p>

  <h3>IP warmup</h3>
  <p>Gradually increasing send volume from a new IP so receivers learn its behaviour. Required for dedicated IPs; not required for shared IPs you're sending through.</p>

  <h2>M</h2>
  <h3>MTA (Mail Transfer Agent)</h3>
  <p>The server that sends and routes mail. In cold-email tools, the "sending engine" is effectively the MTA.</p>

  <h2>O</h2>
  <h3>OOO (Out of Office)</h3>
  <p>Auto-reply indicating the recipient is unavailable. Warmbly classifies OOO replies and suppresses them from sequence engagement metrics.</p>

  <h2>P</h2>
  <h3>Pool (warmup)</h3>
  <p>A group of warmed mailboxes that send warmup mail to one another. Quality of the pool matters more than size.</p>

  <h3>PTR (Reverse DNS)</h3>
  <p>The DNS record that resolves an IP back to a hostname. Mailbox providers expect outbound mail to come from IPs with matching PTRs.</p>

  <h2>Q</h2>
  <h3>Quarantine</h3>
  <p>The state of a mailbox temporarily removed from the warmup pool and cold sending. Triggered by reputation warning thresholds.</p>

  <h2>R</h2>
  <h3>Reply detection</h3>
  <p>Identifying a recipient's reply to a sent message, even when the reply chain has been forwarded or quoted text changes.</p>

  <h2>S</h2>
  <h3>SPF</h3>
  <p>DNS record listing the servers and services authorised to send mail for a domain.</p>

  <h3>Suppression</h3>
  <p>Excluding a recipient from future sends. Triggered by hard bounce, complaint, unsubscribe, or manual addition.</p>

  <h2>T</h2>
  <h3>TLS</h3>
  <p>Transport-layer encryption used between mail servers (and between Warmbly and your mailbox provider).</p>

  <h2>U</h2>
  <h3>Unified inbox</h3>
  <p>A single interface that shows replies across every connected mailbox in a workspace.</p>
</Learn>
